Currently, the provider name is determined by a [modelToProviderMap](https://github.com/browserbase/stagehand/blob/c5ff8ce2d7467b70a450ca52bc3e03b15280ce1b/lib/llm/LLMProvider.ts#L62C7-L62C25). I believe it'd be better to ask the user to specify the provider manually instead.

Currently, this code works for preview-04-17, but fails for the latest -05-20:
```ts
    this.stagehand = new Stagehand({
      env: 'LOCAL',
      modelName: 'gemini-2.5-flash-preview-04-17',
      // modelName: 'gemini-2.5-flash-preview-05-20', // FAILS because it's not in the mapping
      modelClientOptions: {
        apiKey: process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY
      },
    })
    await this.stagehand.init()
```

At the same time, the current solution makes it harder to use tools like OpenRouter, requiring a custom llm provider.

## Proposed solution:

```ts
    this.stagehand = new Stagehand({
      env: 'LOCAL',
      provider: 'google', // let the user override the provider key
      modelName: 'gemini-2.5-flash-preview-05-20',
      modelClientOptions: {
        apiKey: process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY,
      },
    })
    await this.stagehand.init()
```

With this solution, OpenRouter can be integrated without requiring a custom llm provider class:

```ts
    this.stagehand = new Stagehand({
      env: 'LOCAL',
      provider: 'openai',
      modelName: 'deepseek/deepseek-r1-0528',
      modelClientOptions: {
        apiKey: process.env.OPENROUTER_API_KEY,
        baseURL: 'https://openrouter.ai/api/v1',
      },
    })
    await this.stagehand.init()
```

Bug Description
When attempting to use Stagehand with a custom LLM by providing a custom llmClient object to the constructor, the SDK throws an UnsupportedModelError. This occurs even when following the official documentation's example for "OpenAI-compatible APIs", which involves wrapping an OpenAI client instance in a custom class that extends LLMClient.

The core issue seems to be that the Stagehand constructor does not correctly bypass its internal provider checks when a custom llmClient is provided, leading to a crash before the custom client's methods are ever called.

